🚀 GitHub Contribution Guide
1. Set Up Git

Install Git: Download Git

Configure Git with your info:

git config --global user.name "Your Name"
git config --global user.email "youremail@example.com"

2. Forking & Cloning
✅ Fork

Go to the repo on GitHub.

Click Fork (top right). This makes a copy under your account.

✅ Clone
git clone https://github.com/YOUR-USERNAME/REPO-NAME.git
cd REPO-NAME

3. Creating a Branch

Always make changes in a new branch (not main):

git checkout -b feature-branch-name


Example:

git checkout -b add-css-exercise

4. Making Changes

Edit files (index.html, style.css, etc.).

Check status:

git status


Stage changes:

git add .


Commit changes:

git commit -m "Added styling for header section"

5. Pushing Changes

Push your branch to GitHub:

git push origin feature-branch-name

6. Creating a Pull Request (PR)

Go to your repo on GitHub.

You’ll see Compare & Pull Request. Click it.

Add title & description:

Title: Add CSS exercise styles

Description: Explain what you did and why.

Click Create Pull Request.

⚠️ If it’s your own repo, you can merge directly.
⚠️ If it’s an open-source repo, maintainers will review and merge.

7. Syncing with Upstream Repo (Important for Open Source)

If the original repo updates, you need to pull changes:

git remote add upstream https://github.com/ORIGINAL-OWNER/REPO-NAME.git
git fetch upstream
git checkout main
git merge upstream/main
git push origin main

8. Contribution Best Practices

Follow repo’s Contributing Guidelines (look for CONTRIBUTING.md).

Follow code style (indentation, naming).

Write clear commit messages:

feat: add new quiz component
fix: correct typo in CSS class
docs: update README


Make small PRs (easy to review).

Be polite & responsive to feedback.

9. Tracking Your Contributions

Contributions show in your GitHub profile graph (green squares).

Contributions count if you:

Commit to a public repo.

Open/merge PRs.

Review PRs.

Open issues.

Contribute to discussions.

10. Daily GitHub Growth Strategy

Start your own project → commit daily.

Contribute to open-source → fork, fix issues, send PRs.

Write good README.md → helps others use your repo.

Join issues labeled good first issue on GitHub → beginner friendly.
